{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d8fb2a04-dd5c-4a15-b145-2e91766de59a","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK moved forward → workloads need to catch up → `dotnet workload update`.\n\nIf issues persist after updating, try:\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6be488e4-a5a3-4259-b80e-bf7e21fe6e30","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":236,"requestId":"B80B:18AE3E:122889:17DF4D:69FFD772"},"id":"4f065d04-4ab4-47b7-a46e-555a22d5f286","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:55:21.406Z","parentId":"60fd9b86-009c-4408-b5e0-4f5e71cd1a4b"}
